A Linear Search Algorithm is the simplest searching technique used to find an element in a list or array.

ðŸ‘‰ Definition:
Linear search goes through each element in the list one by one, from start to end, until it either finds the target element or reaches the end of the list.

ðŸ”¹ Steps of Linear Search:
Start from the first element of the array.
Compare the current element with the target (the value you are searching for).
If the current element matches the target â†’ return its index (position).
If not, move to the next element.
If the entire array is checked and no match is found â†’ return not found (e.g., -1).


ðŸ”¹ Example:
Suppose you have an array:
[10, 25, 30, 45, 50]
You want to search for 30.
Compare 10 with 30 â†’ not equal
Compare 25 with 30 â†’ not equal
Compare 30 with 30 â†’ âœ… found at index 2

import java.util.Scanner;

public class LinearSearch {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
    int[] arr={1,21,32,42,26,2,1,2,1,3,1,321,31};
    Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);
    System.out.println("Enter the elements");
    int target=sc.nextInt();
    int ans=linearSearch(arr,target);
        System.out.println(ans);
    }
    static int linearSearch(int[] arr ,int target){
        if(arr.length==target){
            return -1;
        }

       // finding index of ele
      //  for (int i=0; i< arr.length; i++){
            for (int i=3; i< 8; i++){
            int ele=arr[i];
            if(target==ele){
               return  i;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
